    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is dollar cost averaging (DCA)?</h3>
        <p>Dollar cost averaging is an investment strategy where you divide your total investment amount into equal periodic purchases regardless of the asset's price. By buying at regular intervals, you purchase more shares when prices are low and fewer when prices are high, which can reduce the impact of volatility on your average cost per share.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Is dollar cost averaging better than lump sum investing?</h3>
        <p>Historically, lump sum investing outperforms DCA about two-thirds of the time because markets tend to go up over time. However, DCA reduces the risk of investing at a market peak and can be psychologically easier for investors who are uncomfortable deploying a large sum all at once. The best strategy depends on your risk tolerance and market outlook.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How often should I invest with dollar cost averaging?</h3>
        <p>The most common DCA frequencies are weekly, biweekly (every two weeks), or monthly. Monthly is the most popular because it aligns with pay schedules. Research shows that the specific frequency matters less than consistency—the key is to invest regularly regardless of market conditions.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Does DCA work in a bear market?</h3>
        <p>DCA tends to shine in bear markets and volatile sideways markets. When prices are falling, your fixed investment amount buys more shares at lower prices, reducing your average cost basis. When the market eventually recovers, you benefit from having accumulated shares at discounted prices.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is the difference between DCA and regular investing?</h3>
        <p>True DCA involves taking a lump sum you already have and spreading it out over time. Regular investing (sometimes called automatic investing) means investing new money as you earn it, such as contributing from each paycheck. While the mechanics are similar, DCA is specifically a strategy for deploying existing capital, whereas regular investing is about building wealth incrementally.</p>
      </div>
